08087nam a22011415i 9781614516972DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97816145169727 a10.1515/97816145169722doi  a(DE-B1597)426913  a(OCoLC)1065414788  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB751.Z7bA733 2018 7aPHI0120002bisacsh04a181.522304aThe Arabic, Hebrew and Latin Reception of Avicenna's Physics and Cosmology /ced. by Dag Nikolaus Hasse, Amos Bertolacci. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 549 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScientia Graeco-Arabica ,x1868-7172 ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChanging Motion: The Place (and Misplace) of Avicenna’s Theory of Motion in the Post-Classical Islamic World -- tAvicenna’s al-ḥikma al-mutaʿāliya. Meaning and Early Reception -- tAvicennian Elements in Faḫr al-Dīn al-Rāzī’s Discussion of Place, Void and Directions in the al-Mabāḥiṯ al-mašriqiyya -- tThe Existence of Time in Faḫr al-Dīn al-Rāzī’s al-Maṭālib al-ʿāliya -- tTime and Mind-Dependence in Sayf al-Dīn al-Āmidī’s Abkār al-afkār -- tA Map of Averroes’ Criticism against Avicenna: Physics, De caelo, De generatione et corruptione and Meteorology -- tAvicennian Sources in Abraham Ibn Daud’s Natural Philosophy? -- tThe Medieval Hebrew Reception of Avicenna’s Account of the Formation and Perseverance of Dry Land: Between Bold Naturalism and Fideist Literalism -- tNotes on Anonymous Twelfth-Century Translations of Philosophical Texts from Arabic into Latin on the Iberian Peninsula -- tAvicenna’s Influence on William of Auvergne’s Theory of Efficient Causes -- t‘Averroes ubique Avicennam persequitur’: Albert the Great’s Approach to the Physics of the Šifāʾ in the Light of Averroes’ Criticisms -- tAvicenna’s Physics in Roger Bacon’s Communia naturalium -- tFollower or Opponent of Aristotle? The Critical Reception of Avicenna’s Meteorology in the Latin World and the Legacy of Alfred the Englishman -- tIndex of Avicenna’s Works with Passages Cited -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAvicenna (Ibn Sīnā) greatly influenced later medieval thinking about the earth and the cosmos, not only in his own civilization, but also in Hebrew and Latin cultures. The studies presented in this volume discuss the reception of prominent theories by Avicenna from the early 11th century onwards by thinkers like Averroes, Fahraddin ar-Razi, Samuel ibn Tibbon or Albertus Magnus. Among the topics which receive particular attention are the definition and existence of motion and time. Other important topics are covered too, such as Avicenna’s theories of vacuum, causality, elements, substantial change, minerals, floods and mountains. It emerges, among other things, that Avicenna inherited to the discussion an acute sense for the epistemological status of natural science and for the mental and concrete existence of its objects. The volume also addresses the philological and historical circumstances of the textual tradition and sheds light on the translators Dominicus Gundisalvi, Avendauth and Alfred of Sareshel in particular. The articles of this volume are presented by scholars who convened in 2013 to discuss their research on the influence of Avicenna’s physics and cosmology in the Villa Vigoni, Italy.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aHebrew literature, MedievalxPhilosophy. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aPhysicsxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aAvicenna. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArabic philosophy.  aAvicenna.  aHebrew philosophy.  amedieval philosophy.1 aAd